Been putting this post off. I wanted to write more but the words aren‚Äôt coming. Saturday a week ago we had to send my beloved Smokey across the rainbow bridge. He had been sick over a month and slowly stopped eating and drinking. After multiple vet visits and numerous tests we found he had cancer. Unfortunately his chest and abdominal cavities started filling with fluid so fast we didn‚Äôt have time to do more tests to determine treatment. He struggled to breathe. He was slowly starving.   He was suffering and I couldn‚Äôt allow that to continue.   My heart is broken. My sweet Smokes had been with us almost 12 years. He was the first cat I had after a few decades of losing my last. He was the best sweetest companion. Even at the end.   He was held in all our hands as he slipped away. He purred until the end. The usual vet we saw wasn‚Äôt there so she called us the next day and told us it was the right thing not to wait for her. He was just getting worse and worse.   I miss him every day.   I have his nose prints and paw prints. I will  Be getting those tattooed in the fall as he will always be with me.   Hug your fur babies. You never know when they will be called across the rainbow bridge.

post_body: health update/diatribe/infodump BUT THERE‚ÄôS A CAT VIDEO AT THE END Dearest reader: This should be a simple health update but instead it‚Äôs an obnoxiously detailed info-dump written by the kind of person who knows more than most people about American health insurance but is still surprised at how it continues to find new and innovative ways to suck. If this is not the type of thing your brain or nervous system wants to wrap itself around I don‚Äôt blame you one bit but if it is I hope you‚Äôll at least walk away having learned something or being at least mildly entertained. If not feel free to  SCROLL TO THE END FOR A HTDIO-ADJACENT CAT VIDEO! When last we left our third-or-fourth-favorite mildly niche-famous T-list Broadway person she was finally on the brink of getting a brain and pituitary MRI. This was supposed to happen on Friday.  But I wasn‚Äôt allowed to get the MRI on Friday because Cigna‚Äôs pre-authorization was still pending and there was nothing my doctor could do to escalate its urgency nor could they withdraw the order. They couldn‚Äôt do anything at all until the third-party organization that approves the pre-authorizations signed off on its medical necessity.   Look I get it. This is an expensive and labor-intensive procedure so they have to be thorough. I mean sure my doctor said it was medically necessary and sure they sent the additional clinical information to confirm its medically necessity and sure every order at every stage was marked as urgently medically necessary and it was sent for processing on Monday but how can they REALLY be sure it‚Äôs medically necessary until my case is also reviewed by doctors who have NEVER seen me and don‚Äôt work weekends or holidays and will get around to reviewing it at their own leisure? The folks at the radiology clinic rescheduled me in their next available spot and maintained that they‚Äôd contact me as soon as possible to fill any upcoming cancellation spots.  A ridiculous mildly annoying setback was that their next available appointment wasn‚Äôt until July 26. They couldn‚Äôt attempt to book me at any of the other dozens of clinics affiliated with this hospital network because the pre-authorization is site-specific which is like buying someone a gift card from the Starbucks on my block only to find out that they won‚Äôt honor it at the Starbucks two blocks down perfectly reasonable because I‚Äôm sure every site has differences that can‚Äôt be perceived from a patient perspective.  Oh and the existence of a pending pre-authorization prevented them from doing the MRI that day even if I‚Äôd had $8K in cash to pay out of pocket for the procedure. Which is perfectly reasonable because why shouldn‚Äôt American healthcare policy punish rich people too? I‚Äôm sure it‚Äôs many flavors of unethical for one doctor to do something without the approval of another doctor even though the doctor whose approval it hangs on has NEVER SEEN ME.  One fellow in particular‚ÄìI‚Äôll call him Quincy‚Äìgave me some insider info on how to prepare for the types of advocacy he‚Äôs had to do in the past with this particular pre-authorization team and which numbers to call and questions to ask. He isn‚Äôt technically supposed to know this stuff and also isn‚Äôt technically supposed to share it but says he does it all the time anyway‚Äìhence why I‚Äôm keeping him anonymous. Quincy isn‚Äôt his real name but Quincy is a real one and I took in his information like a medieval warrior selecting the choicest armor to prepare for battle the informed and fully compliant patient I strive to be.  Anyway a few persistent phone calls later a Cigna rep informed me that the middlemen would approve the pre-authorization for the MRI on the condition that I get the procedure done at a standalone radiology facility instead of a hospital-affiliated facility. Which is like buying someone a gift card that could only be honored at Starbucks kiosks located inside Target stores but not at a standalone Starbucks or anywhere else in Target perfectly reasonable I know the insurance companies don‚Äôt wanna have to spend hospital prices any more than I do. So I spent a great deal of time yesterday looking up non-hospital-affiliated radiology clinics that were in-network.  I made an appointment with one clinic for Thursday. But I also made an appointment request at a different clinic for Monday morning just in case they could see me sooner‚Äìbecause I knew this clinic didn‚Äôt accept Medicare or Medicaid and were therefore exempt from the requirement of third-party pre-authorization. (Pro-tip: even if you do have Medicare or Medicaid always try to bypass pre-authorization for diagnostic procedures especially if you have a particularly high in-network deductible‚Äìit‚Äôs entirely possible that paying out of pocket for a service at an out-of-network provider could cost less than the amount you‚Äôd have to pay towards your deductible at at in-network facility. American math.)  THIS MORNING I woke up at 8am to a phone call from the latter clinic saying that if I sent them the doctor‚Äôs prescription they could pre-authorize the procedure and see me tomorrow. So that‚Äôs what I did‚Ä¶and then I got an email saying that they couldn‚Äôt accept a prescription for an MRI with and without contrast because they don‚Äôt have contrast at that facility. Which is like finally securing a coveted reservation at an elite steakhouse only to find out they don‚Äôt season their steak or even have steak sauce perfectly reasonable because not everyone needs contrast but I do so that place was out.  But as far as I‚Äôve been told Thursday‚Äôs appointment should go off without a hitch as long as I call EviCore (the pre-authorization middlemen) tomorrow morning to tell them all about the not-hospital that will be giving me a not-hospital-priced MRI so that they can grant the pre-authorization at long last.  Perhaps if I plead my case and bat my eyes at them real cute-like through the phone  they‚Äôll give me some other reason why it‚Äôs actually not medically necessary for me to know definitively whether or not I have a literal brain tumor I can get seen even sooner than Thursday.  FUNNY STORY THOUGH‚Ä¶  A couple weeks ago I was talking to a friend from church who was going through a lot of the same stuff as I was and I was like ‚Äúidk maybe get your cortisol checked?‚Äù and lo and behold he messaged me back a few days ago saying that he‚Äôd found a new doctor and asked him to do just that and WITHIN A DAY his doctor ordered ALL the labs I‚Äôd fought for (serum blood cortisol low-dose dexamethasone suppression test 24-hour urine saliva etc.) AND an MRI for suspected Cushing‚Äôs.  And he completed ALL OF THAT within a week.  Although he did have to suffer for quite a while before I floated the possibility of Cushing‚Äôs just like my friend Alan had to suffer for years before his own endocrinologists floated the possibility of Cushing‚Äôs. Still they both got that MRI the second it WAS floated without a fight and I‚Äôm genuinely happy for them.  But I can‚Äôt help wondering how much quicker and easier this whole process would have been for me if I were a man. Or if I was neurotypical. Or if I still had a choice about whether or not to disclose being autistic. But mostly if I were a man.  THIS IS THE END! HERE IS THE HTDIO-ADJACENT CAT VIDEO YOU WERE PROMISED! (Pro-tip: even if you do have Medicare or Medicaid always try to bypass pre-authorization for diagnostic procedures especially if you have a particularly high in-network deductible‚Äìit‚Äôs entirely possible that paying out of pocket for a service at an out-of-network provider could cost less than the amount you‚Äôd have to pay towards your deductible at at in-network facility. American math.)  THIS MORNING I woke up at 8am to a phone call from the latter clinic saying that if I sent them the doctor‚Äôs prescription they could pre-authorize the procedure and see me tomorrow. So that‚Äôs what I did‚Ä¶and then I got an email saying that they couldn‚Äôt accept a prescription for an MRI with and without contrast because they don‚Äôt have contrast at that facility. Which is like finally securing a coveted reservation at an elite steakhouse only to find out they don‚Äôt season their steak or even have steak sauce perfectly reasonable because not everyone needs contrast but I do so that place was out.  But as far as I‚Äôve been told Thursday‚Äôs appointment should go off without a hitch as long as I call EviCore (the pre-authorization middlemen) tomorrow morning to tell them all about the not-hospital that will be giving me a not-hospital-priced MRI so that they can grant the pre-authorization at long last.  Perhaps if I plead my case and bat my eyes at them real cute-like through the phone  they‚Äôll give me some other reason why it‚Äôs actually not medically necessary for me to know definitively whether or not I have a literal brain tumor I can get seen even sooner than Thursday.  FUNNY STORY THOUGH‚Ä¶  A couple weeks ago I was talking to a friend from church who was going through a lot of the same stuff as I was and I was like ‚Äúidk maybe get your cortisol checked?‚Äù and lo and behold he messaged me back a few days ago saying that he‚Äôd found a new doctor and asked him to do just that and WITHIN A DAY his doctor ordered ALL the labs I‚Äôd fought for (serum blood cortisol low-dose dexamethasone suppression test 24-hour urine saliva etc.) AND an MRI for suspected Cushing‚Äôs.  And he completed ALL OF THAT within a week.  Although he did have to suffer for quite a while before I floated the possibility of Cushing‚Äôs just like my friend Alan had to suffer for years before his own endocrinologists floated the possibility of Cushing‚Äôs. Still they both got that MRI the second it WAS floated without a fight and I‚Äôm genuinely happy for them.  But I can‚Äôt help wondering how much quicker and easier this whole process would have been for me if I were a man. Or if I was neurotypical. Or if I still had a choice about whether or not to disclose being autistic. But mostly if I were a man.  THIS IS THE END! HERE IS THE HTDIO-ADJACENT CAT VIDEO YOU WERE PROMISED! I‚Äôm fostering my friends‚Äô exquisite tuxedo princessfloof for a few weeks. Chevy and Tex are being very accommodating foster siblings but she‚Äôs much younger and is used to being the only pet so naturally it took her a while to acclimate.  But there was one thing she took to immediately: the How to Dance in Ohio fidget spinner.
I‚Äôm never getting this done.

post_body: Posting my cat until I get bored. Day 8.

Hey there everyone  For those who had been following along in regard to the recent situation here I had to go back to the vet with both Oreo and Pudding yesterday. Oreo has been throwing up a lot this past week and I was concerned. Pudding also threw up yesterday. He threw up his entire lunch right after he ate and there was a big hairball stuck inside. I was concerned that maybe the yarn would surface next. So far it hasn‚Äôt.  Oreo did some blood tests as well as another X-ray. His iron levels are almost back to normal which is great but the tests also show that he has some sort of infection. The vet isn‚Äôt sure what it is but most likely from everything he just recently went through. He was given an atibiotic injection as well as an anti-nausea injection. I also have some anti-nausea pills for him for 4 days. We will see how the antibiotic does and if he still continues to throw up he wil have to see a specialist for an ultrasound. There was nothing out of the ordinary in his X-ray.  Pudding was checked too and everything seems OK with him. I hope that Oreo will feel better with the antibiotic and we won‚Äôt have to see the specialist. If we do we will have to make the trek to Montreal and it will cost a few thousand dollars. I will keep you posted on what happens next. Let‚Äôs everyone keep our fingers and paws crossed that this will be the end of it.  Thanks to everyone for your kind words prayers and continued support. They‚Äôre sincerely appreciated.  Tina.
